  <!-- Patronal festivals: besides the national holidays, Italian law recognizes a local public
       holiday on the feast day of a comune's patron saint (L. 27 maggio 1949, n. 260, art. 5 as
       amended by L. 31 marzo 1954, n. 90). Only Rome's is codified directly in statute (D.P.R.
       28 dicembre 1985, n. 792); elsewhere the day off rests on long-standing local custom
       recognized through collective labour agreements, but is a genuine non-working day for
       schools and most offices all the same. Only the regional capital is modelled here for
       each region. -->

